 the drinks were getting sweeter, the racial divide was getting more bitter—Black Americans in search of a drink, entertainment, or a hotel room had to depend on the Green Book for advice on places where they would be welcome and safe. And the Cold War and Space Race proceeded ominously throughout this period, as technological advances alternately thrilled and terrified.The third installment in Cecelia Tichi’s tour of the cocktails enjoyed in various historical eras, Midcentury Cocktails brings a time of limitless possibilities to life though the cocktails created, named, and consumed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh  aAllen Ginsberg.  aAtomic Age.  aAtomic.  aAudrey Hepburn.  aBachelor pad.  aBachelor.  aBar car.  aBarbizon.  aBetty Friedan.  aBimini.  aBoeing.  aBourbon.  aCocktails.  aCorporation.  aCuba.  aDon the Beachcomber.  aDonn Beach.  aDouglas.  aDr. Strangelove.  aDwight D. Eisenhower.  aEdward Albee.  aErnest Hemingway.  aExecutive.  aFeminine Mystique.  aFeminism.  aFrank Sinatra.  aFreedom.  aGin.  aGrace Metalious.  aGray flannel.  aGreen Book.  aHelen Gurley Brown.  aHemingway.  aHugh Hefner.  aJacqueline Susann.  aJames Baldwin.  aJet Set.  aKeith Hefner.  aKey West.  aMademoiselle.  aMary Hemingway.  aMary McCarthy.  aMax Shulman.  aMetro North Railroad.  aMid-Century.  aMolly Brown.  aNegro.  aNew Haven Railroad.  aNew York.  aNightclub.  aPan American Airlines.  aPauline Pfeiffer.  aPlayboy Bunny.  aPlayboy Club.  aPlayboy Magazine.  aPlayboy.  aPulitzer.  aRoad.  aScotch.  aStewardess.  aSuburb.  aT. S. Eliot Norman Mailer.  aTheatre.  aThomas Mario.  aT